WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.920 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.920 --> 00:00:04.320 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.320 --> 00:00:05.760 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:11.820 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:13.640 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So last
time, just quickly

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:19.040 align:middle line:84%
recall, we looked at a
function on some interval

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:25.740 align:middle line:84%
into R. We looked at a
partition, P. So here,

00:00:25.740 --> 00:00:28.360 align:middle line:84%
we have the interval
from a to b.

00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:35.760 align:middle line:84%
Then we have a partition,
x0, x1, up to, say, xn.

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:41.820 align:middle line:84%
We looked at Mi, which was the
sup, on this little interval

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:45.960 align:middle line:90%
here from xi minus 1 to xi of f.

00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:51.800 align:middle line:84%
We looked at little
mi, which was the inf.

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:53.150 align:middle line:90%
f here was bounded again.

00:00:53.150 --> 00:00:57.920 align:middle line:90%


00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:03.820 align:middle line:84%
And inf on the same
interval, xi minus 1 to xi.

00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:07.460 align:middle line:84%
And then we looked at the
upper and the lower sum.

00:01:07.460 --> 00:01:11.580 align:middle line:84%
So we looked at the
upper and lower sum

00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:13.940 align:middle line:90%
with respect to this partition.

00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:19.700 align:middle line:84%
So this here was the sum
of Mi and then delta xi

00:01:19.700 --> 00:01:24.300 align:middle line:84%
and the lower sum for
this partition, which

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:31.620 align:middle line:84%
was the sum of this smaller mi's
delta xi, where the delta xi was

00:01:31.620 --> 00:01:37.860 align:middle line:84%
the length of these little
intervals here, like that.

00:01:37.860 --> 00:01:40.620 align:middle line:84%
And then it was
Riemann integrable.

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:48.140 align:middle line:84%
Then we looked at the lower
and the upper Riemann integral.

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:54.580 align:middle line:84%
So we looked at the upper
and lower Riemann integral.

00:01:54.580 --> 00:02:01.920 align:middle line:84%
This here was now the inf
of these upper integrals

00:02:01.920 --> 00:02:03.760 align:middle line:90%
over all partitions.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:12.840 align:middle line:84%
And the lower one, that
was the sup of the lower

00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:17.080 align:middle line:90%
sums over all partitions.

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:27.360 align:middle line:84%
And then we said that f is
Riemann integrable if those two

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:30.460 align:middle line:84%
numbers are the same,
if the upper one here,

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:33.200 align:middle line:84%
which is always bigger or
equal to the lower one,

00:02:33.200 --> 00:02:37.960 align:middle line:84%
if that is actually equal to
the lower one, the lower Riemann

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:40.328 align:middle line:90%
integral.

00:02:40.328 --> 00:02:43.300 align:middle line:90%
And if this is the case--

00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:45.880 align:middle line:90%
so this here is--

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:48.000 align:middle line:84%
it's Riemann
integrable if and only

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:49.920 align:middle line:84%
if these two numbers
are the same.

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:53.120 align:middle line:84%
And in that case, we wrote--
for this common number,

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:55.040 align:middle line:90%
we wrote just the--

00:02:55.040 --> 00:02:59.020 align:middle line:84%
we wrote it as the
Riemann integral.

00:02:59.020 --> 00:03:06.000 align:middle line:84%
So now, there was this parallel
to things we have done before.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.860 align:middle line:84%
There was these algebraic
rules that we talked about

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:11.040 align:middle line:90%
at the very end.

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:12.705 align:middle line:90%
So what were those?

00:03:12.705 --> 00:03:15.740 align:middle line:90%


00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:24.060 align:middle line:84%
If you take a function
that is Riemann integrable,

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:31.140 align:middle line:84%
and you take c is a constant,
then the product here

00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:32.920 align:middle line:90%
is also Riemann integrable.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:37.180 align:middle line:90%


00:03:37.180 --> 00:03:43.020 align:middle line:84%
And the integral of
the product is just--

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:46.500 align:middle line:84%
product function
is just the product

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:53.020 align:middle line:84%
of c with the Riemann
integral of f.

00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:55.360 align:middle line:90%
So that was 1.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:04:00.480 align:middle line:84%
2 is that if you have a second
function, so in addition to f,

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:07.746 align:middle line:84%
you also have a g, and they're
both Riemann integrable,

00:04:07.746 --> 00:04:12.220 align:middle line:84%
then the sum here is
also Riemann integrable.

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:15.840 align:middle line:90%


00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:25.040 align:middle line:84%
And the integral of
the sum is equal to--

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:26.480 align:middle line:90%
from a to b--

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:28.930 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the sum of
the Riemann integral.

00:04:28.930 --> 00:04:31.960 align:middle line:90%


00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:33.420 align:middle line:90%
Let's prove this one here.

00:04:33.420 --> 00:04:36.200 align:middle line:90%


00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:38.240 align:middle line:90%
I won't prove the first one.

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:40.400 align:middle line:90%
But let's prove the second one.

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:42.600 align:middle line:90%
So this is 2.

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:45.160 align:middle line:84%
Now, to prove this,
let me remind you

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:53.860 align:middle line:84%
about one of the lemmas
that we had last time.

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:58.060 align:middle line:84%
We were talking about that
this was a useful lemma

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:01.900 align:middle line:84%
to determine whether a function
was Riemann integrable.

00:05:01.900 --> 00:05:07.860 align:middle line:84%
So recall this from
last time, that you

00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:14.280 align:middle line:84%
have the following lemma,
that f, again, is bounded.

00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:21.940 align:middle line:84%
So f is Riemann
integrable if and only

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:28.260 align:middle line:84%
if, for all epsilon
greater than 0,

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:32.180 align:middle line:84%
there exists a partition
of this interval here

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:36.660 align:middle line:84%
such that the upper
sum, which is always

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:46.260 align:middle line:84%
bigger than the lower sum, this
one here, minus the lower sum--

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:49.100 align:middle line:84%
so this number is
always positive.

00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:55.120 align:middle line:84%
But if, for all epsilon, you
can make this difference here

00:05:55.120 --> 00:05:58.600 align:middle line:84%
smaller, then you can find a
partition so that you have that.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:00.060 align:middle line:90%
You proved that last time.

00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:02.600 align:middle line:90%


00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:05.540 align:middle line:84%
So now, let's go to
the proof of this.

00:06:05.540 --> 00:06:09.920 align:middle line:90%


00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:11.180 align:middle line:90%
So proof of 2.

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:18.520 align:middle line:90%


00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:28.280 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon greater
than 0, since f here

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:34.160 align:middle line:84%
is Riemann
integrable, then there

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:45.920 align:middle line:84%
exists a partition, P1,
such that the upper sum

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:54.320 align:middle line:84%
minus the lower sum is
less than epsilon over 2.

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:58.140 align:middle line:84%
This is because the function
f was Riemann integrable.

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:07.620 align:middle line:84%
And likewise-- likewise,
since g is Riemann integrable,

00:07:07.620 --> 00:07:19.220 align:middle line:84%
so there exists a second
partition, P2, so that, for g,

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:21.980 align:middle line:90%
you have the same thing--

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:23.160 align:middle line:90%
for g and P2.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:25.300 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, this is g.

00:07:25.300 --> 00:07:29.020 align:middle line:84%
This upper sum
minus the lower sum

00:07:29.020 --> 00:07:33.460 align:middle line:84%
for g with respect to
this second partition,

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:35.700 align:middle line:84%
this here, is less
than epsilon over 2.

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:40.140 align:middle line:90%


00:07:40.140 --> 00:07:42.130 align:middle line:90%
So now you let P here--

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:46.080 align:middle line:90%


00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:58.600 align:middle line:84%
so now let P be
the partition that

00:07:58.600 --> 00:08:12.560 align:middle line:84%
has all the dividing
points of P1,

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:30.640 align:middle line:84%
together with all the
dividing points of P2.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:38.509 align:middle line:84%
So it has the partitions that
are in either one of the two,

00:08:38.509 --> 00:08:40.500 align:middle line:90%
or both.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:44.580 align:middle line:84%
And so now we know that--
so this just means that--

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:57.740 align:middle line:84%
so P here is a refinement
of both P1 and P2.

00:08:57.740 --> 00:09:00.380 align:middle line:90%


00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:02.260 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
actually, when

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:04.140 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at
this, if you're

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:10.800 align:middle line:84%
looking at this upper
sum minus this lower sum,

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:13.860 align:middle line:84%
remember that if you
go to a refinement,

00:09:13.860 --> 00:09:16.020 align:middle line:90%
then this here goes down.

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:17.440 align:middle line:90%
And this here goes up.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:19.460 align:middle line:84%
So it means that
this difference here

00:09:19.460 --> 00:09:25.190 align:middle line:84%
would be less than or
equal to what it is for P1.

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:32.980 align:middle line:90%


00:09:32.980 --> 00:09:35.600 align:middle line:84%
And this was, of course,
less than epsilon over 2.

00:09:35.600 --> 00:09:37.060 align:middle line:90%
That was how it was chosen.

00:09:37.060 --> 00:09:41.660 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, if you're
looking at the upper sum

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:52.800 align:middle line:84%
for g with respect to P, P here
is a refinement of P2 also.

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:56.800 align:middle line:84%
So this means that you have
that this difference here

00:09:56.800 --> 00:10:04.160 align:middle line:84%
is less or equal to the
upper sum of g with respect

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:09.880 align:middle line:84%
to P2 minus this lower
sum with respect to P2.

00:10:09.880 --> 00:10:11.900 align:middle line:84%
And that's less
than epsilon over 2.

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:14.800 align:middle line:90%


00:10:14.800 --> 00:10:19.760 align:middle line:84%
But this means now that
if you now take the--

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:21.110 align:middle line:90%
so now, if you take--

00:10:21.110 --> 00:10:29.600 align:middle line:90%


00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:36.000 align:middle line:84%
so now, if you take
an interval here of--

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:41.300 align:middle line:90%
this is from xi minus 1 to xi.

00:10:41.300 --> 00:10:45.080 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking
at this sum here--

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:46.980 align:middle line:84%
you have to be a little
bit careful here.

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:50.700 align:middle line:84%
But if you're looking at
the sum on this integral,

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:56.140 align:middle line:84%
the sum here is less or equal
to the sup of what f is--

00:10:56.140 --> 00:11:01.580 align:middle line:90%
this is on this interval here.

00:11:01.580 --> 00:11:04.660 align:middle line:84%
On this interval,
this function here

00:11:04.660 --> 00:11:12.195 align:middle line:84%
is less than the sup
of f plus the sup of g

00:11:12.195 --> 00:11:13.070 align:middle line:90%
on the same interval.

00:11:13.070 --> 00:11:20.276 align:middle line:90%


00:11:20.276 --> 00:11:25.380 align:middle line:84%
And it's, of course,
bigger or equal to what--

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:38.810 align:middle line:84%
it is the inf of f plus the
inf of g on that same interval.

00:11:38.810 --> 00:11:42.960 align:middle line:90%


00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:45.020 align:middle line:84%
Why do I say you have to
be a little bit careful

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:53.480 align:middle line:84%
is that the inf of the sum could
be strictly larger than this.

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:55.840 align:middle line:84%
And it could be
strictly less than that.

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:58.720 align:middle line:84%
But you certainly
have this statement.

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:04.180 align:middle line:84%
Just thinking about, if f and
g was the same up to a sign,

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:09.920 align:middle line:84%
if g was like minus f, then
the sum would be dead 0.

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:13.800 align:middle line:84%
But one of the functions may
be negative on this interval,

00:12:13.800 --> 00:12:15.300 align:middle line:90%
and the other one was positive.

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:18.720 align:middle line:84%
So you see, for the sum
here, could be dead 0.

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:21.140 align:middle line:84%
But these two numbers,
one would be positive.

00:12:21.140 --> 00:12:22.600 align:middle line:90%
The other would be negative.

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:24.960 align:middle line:84%
But you certainly
have this inequality.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:30.240 align:middle line:84%
And so, of course, this
implies that on this interval,

00:12:30.240 --> 00:12:39.380 align:middle line:84%
the sup of the sum here
is less than the sup

00:12:39.380 --> 00:12:42.590 align:middle line:90%
of the sum of the sups--

00:12:42.590 --> 00:12:49.100 align:middle line:90%


00:12:49.100 --> 00:12:51.280 align:middle line:84%
sum of the sups on
the same intervals--

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:58.060 align:middle line:90%


00:12:58.060 --> 00:13:01.660 align:middle line:90%
and likewise for the inf.

00:13:01.660 --> 00:13:05.900 align:middle line:90%


00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:07.680 align:middle line:90%
So you have this thing here.

00:13:07.680 --> 00:13:09.780 align:middle line:84%
And you have that
this thing here

00:13:09.780 --> 00:13:14.900 align:middle line:84%
is clearly bigger or equal to
the inf of the same function,

00:13:14.900 --> 00:13:20.740 align:middle line:84%
which is the sum of the
two, on this interval here.

00:13:20.740 --> 00:13:25.680 align:middle line:84%
And that is, of course,
bigger than this sum here.

00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:33.380 align:middle line:90%


00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:36.560 align:middle line:90%
So this here, this number here--

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:42.640 align:middle line:84%
you see, this here is like
Mi for the function f.

00:13:42.640 --> 00:13:45.760 align:middle line:90%
This is what this number is.

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:48.520 align:middle line:84%
And this here is
like-- this number here

00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:54.760 align:middle line:84%
is like capital Mi
for the function g.

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:58.480 align:middle line:84%
And this here-- this
here is like little--

00:13:58.480 --> 00:14:02.600 align:middle line:84%
this here is like little
mi for the function f.

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:08.080 align:middle line:84%
And this number here is
little mi for the function g.

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:15.880 align:middle line:84%
So what we have here
is that mi for f plus--

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:18.820 align:middle line:90%
sorry, let me write this--

00:14:18.820 --> 00:14:22.720 align:middle line:90%


00:14:22.720 --> 00:14:24.020 align:middle line:90%
let me write it over here.

00:14:24.020 --> 00:14:35.140 align:middle line:90%


00:14:35.140 --> 00:14:39.380 align:middle line:84%
So what we have is that we
have little mi for the function

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:44.500 align:middle line:84%
f plus little mi
for the function g

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:50.980 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to
little mi for the sum, which

00:14:50.980 --> 00:14:56.340 align:middle line:84%
is, of course, less than
the sup of the same sum

00:14:56.340 --> 00:14:57.520 align:middle line:90%
on the same interval.

00:14:57.520 --> 00:15:00.660 align:middle line:90%
So this is this.

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:06.540 align:middle line:84%
And that's less or equal
to the sup of f on that

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:12.120 align:middle line:90%
interval plus this here of g.

00:15:12.120 --> 00:15:15.260 align:middle line:90%
So you have that inequality.

00:15:15.260 --> 00:15:18.080 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
this means, of course,

00:15:18.080 --> 00:15:19.900 align:middle line:90%
that the contribution--

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:26.796 align:middle line:84%
so if you're looking at
this upper sum for this--

00:15:26.796 --> 00:15:31.640 align:middle line:84%
this upper sum for the sum of
these two functions with respect

00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:37.960 align:middle line:84%
to P, this here, the
contribution you get

00:15:37.960 --> 00:15:40.720 align:middle line:90%
is, for the upper, you get this.

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:42.850 align:middle line:84%
And for the lower,
you would get--

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.360 align:middle line:90%


00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:50.480 align:middle line:84%
you'd get this here times the
length of the interval, right?

00:15:50.480 --> 00:15:57.520 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- so again, so what
you get on that little interval,

00:15:57.520 --> 00:16:04.880 align:middle line:84%
the contribution you get is like
Mi f plus g times the length

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:06.270 align:middle line:90%
of the interval--

00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:13.240 align:middle line:84%
this is this-- minus Mi
f plus g times the length

00:16:13.240 --> 00:16:14.400 align:middle line:90%
of the interval.

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:18.320 align:middle line:84%
This is the contribution
that you get here

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:23.200 align:middle line:84%
from this interval-- from
this interval, right?

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:27.660 align:middle line:84%
And because this number
here is less than that,

00:16:27.660 --> 00:16:42.100 align:middle line:84%
then this here is less than Mi f
plus Mi g times delta xi minus--

00:16:42.100 --> 00:16:45.740 align:middle line:84%
and then this thing
here, you see,

00:16:45.740 --> 00:16:48.620 align:middle line:84%
this spreads between
these two here.

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:50.740 align:middle line:84%
Bounds are spread
between those two.

00:16:50.740 --> 00:17:00.300 align:middle line:84%
So this is less than mi f plus
little mi g times delta xi.

00:17:00.300 --> 00:17:04.420 align:middle line:90%


00:17:04.420 --> 00:17:06.560 align:middle line:84%
And now you're summing
over everything.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:09.800 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this thing here is--

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:13.880 align:middle line:84%
so this-- and if you just
split this here, this sum here,

00:17:13.880 --> 00:17:16.500 align:middle line:84%
you can just split
that into two parts,

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:24.279 align:middle line:84%
the Mi f times delta
xi minus little mi

00:17:24.279 --> 00:17:31.810 align:middle line:84%
f times delta xi, and
then plus capital Mi

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:42.200 align:middle line:84%
g delta xi minus
little mi g delta xi.

00:17:42.200 --> 00:17:47.120 align:middle line:84%
So when you're
summing these up, you

00:17:47.120 --> 00:17:54.040 align:middle line:84%
get a U f, P. That's
from this here.

00:17:54.040 --> 00:17:59.216 align:middle line:84%
When you're summing these
up, U f, P minus, sorry, L f,

00:17:59.216 --> 00:18:04.000 align:middle line:84%
P. When you're summing
this up, then you're

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:18.280 align:middle line:90%
getting U g, P minus L g, P.

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:20.470 align:middle line:90%
And so what you get here is--

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:23.240 align:middle line:90%


00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:25.740 align:middle line:84%
again, when you're
summing it up,

00:18:25.740 --> 00:18:31.460 align:middle line:84%
this here gives you-- when you
sum these up, then you get this.

00:18:31.460 --> 00:18:34.600 align:middle line:84%
When you sum this
here up, you get that.

00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:36.120 align:middle line:84%
When you sum this
up, you get that.

00:18:36.120 --> 00:18:38.060 align:middle line:84%
So summing everything
up, you get

00:18:38.060 --> 00:18:43.980 align:middle line:84%
U f plus g, comma,
this partition,

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:51.380 align:middle line:84%
minus L f plus g with
respect to this partition,

00:18:51.380 --> 00:18:55.980 align:middle line:84%
is less or equal
to U f with respect

00:18:55.980 --> 00:19:01.540 align:middle line:84%
to this partition, minus L f
with respect to partition P,

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:13.580 align:middle line:84%
plus U g, P, minus L g,
P. So you're getting that.

00:19:13.580 --> 00:19:19.540 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here, it was a
refinement of the partition P1.

00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:23.140 align:middle line:84%
So this spread here is less
than what it was for P1.

00:19:23.140 --> 00:19:26.800 align:middle line:84%
So this here is less
than epsilon over 2.

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:31.160 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, this here is a
refinement of the partition P2.

00:19:31.160 --> 00:19:34.640 align:middle line:84%
So the spread here is less
than what it is for P2.

00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:36.600 align:middle line:90%
So you're getting this.

00:19:36.600 --> 00:19:38.440 align:middle line:90%
And so this here is epsilon.

00:19:38.440 --> 00:19:41.040 align:middle line:90%
So this gives you the partition.

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:43.520 align:middle line:84%
And so there's two
things you have

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:49.617 align:middle line:84%
to be careful with, that for one
function, you get one partition.

00:19:49.617 --> 00:19:51.700 align:middle line:84%
For the other function,
you get another partition.

00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:55.160 align:middle line:84%
So you're looking
at the subpartition

00:19:55.160 --> 00:19:59.040 align:middle line:84%
that has all of the dividing
points of both of them.

00:19:59.040 --> 00:20:02.420 align:middle line:84%
And the other things you
have to be careful is about--

00:20:02.420 --> 00:20:07.960 align:middle line:84%
and that was embedded here, but
it was actually more clearly

00:20:07.960 --> 00:20:10.160 align:middle line:84%
on one of the other
boards, is that when

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:13.160 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at two
functions, and you're

00:20:13.160 --> 00:20:15.200 align:middle line:84%
looking at a little
interval, and you're

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:19.160 align:middle line:84%
taking the sup of
the sum, then that's

00:20:19.160 --> 00:20:21.460 align:middle line:90%
bounded by the sum of the sup.

00:20:21.460 --> 00:20:25.600 align:middle line:84%
But it's not equal to the
sum, and likewise for the inf.

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:26.100 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:20:26.100 --> 00:20:30.260 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] for a
partition because you always

00:20:30.260 --> 00:20:32.940 align:middle line:90%
have to be [INAUDIBLE]?

00:20:32.940 --> 00:20:36.580 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: I mean,
so there's not.

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:39.580 align:middle line:84%
But the reason it's
not is that once you

00:20:39.580 --> 00:20:43.580 align:middle line:84%
have this general framework,
you wouldn't really get back

00:20:43.580 --> 00:20:45.620 align:middle line:90%
to the partition, actually.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:49.640 align:middle line:90%
So if it was--

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:52.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean, once you
have this solid ,

00:20:52.700 --> 00:20:58.360 align:middle line:90%
foundations then you just write.

00:20:58.360 --> 00:20:59.860 align:middle line:84%
You just write the
integrals, right?

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:01.100 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:21:01.100 --> 00:21:10.800 align:middle line:84%
And so, just on that
note, this dx, this is--

00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:24.480 align:middle line:90%
so this here-- this here is--

00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:26.480 align:middle line:90%
this here is like--

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:28.860 align:middle line:84%
it's referring-- this
is like a giant S.

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:32.440 align:middle line:90%
So it's referring to summation.

00:21:32.440 --> 00:21:36.200 align:middle line:90%
This here is, of course, a d.

00:21:36.200 --> 00:21:38.660 align:middle line:84%
And delta is the
Greek letter for d.

00:21:38.660 --> 00:21:41.280 align:middle line:84%
And so this here, you
should think about this here

00:21:41.280 --> 00:21:47.500 align:middle line:84%
as referring to some sort
of limit of this delta xi.

00:21:47.500 --> 00:21:51.200 align:middle line:90%


00:21:51.200 --> 00:22:01.240 align:middle line:84%
So that was-- let me just talk
a little bit about the other two

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:02.320 align:middle line:90%
rules.

00:22:02.320 --> 00:22:04.570 align:middle line:90%
So one of the other ones is--

00:22:04.570 --> 00:22:07.880 align:middle line:90%


00:22:07.880 --> 00:22:12.150 align:middle line:84%
one of the other ones is that if
you take two functions, f and g

00:22:12.150 --> 00:22:12.650 align:middle line:90%
again--

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:15.200 align:middle line:90%


00:22:15.200 --> 00:22:19.860 align:middle line:84%
so number 3 here was
that if you have f and g,

00:22:19.860 --> 00:22:24.540 align:middle line:84%
they are both integrable
on this interval here.

00:22:24.540 --> 00:22:28.380 align:middle line:84%
And f here is less
or equal to g.

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:32.120 align:middle line:84%
Then it implies that the
integral here is less

00:22:32.120 --> 00:22:38.240 align:middle line:90%
or equal to the integral of g.

00:22:38.240 --> 00:22:41.220 align:middle line:90%


00:22:41.220 --> 00:22:42.940 align:middle line:90%
I won't prove this.

00:22:42.940 --> 00:22:45.400 align:middle line:90%
It's sort of, in a way--

00:22:45.400 --> 00:22:47.580 align:middle line:84%
maybe I'll just say
words, that if you

00:22:47.580 --> 00:22:51.440 align:middle line:84%
take a partition,
then, of course,

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:54.300 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at
some xi minus 1

00:22:54.300 --> 00:22:57.780 align:middle line:90%
and xi, some interval like this.

00:22:57.780 --> 00:23:01.020 align:middle line:84%
And so, if you're looking
at the function f,

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:03.300 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at
the sup of the function

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:10.380 align:middle line:84%
f on this little interval, well
then, obviously, this sup here

00:23:10.380 --> 00:23:15.220 align:middle line:84%
is less than the sup of g, just
because you have this inequality

00:23:15.220 --> 00:23:17.240 align:middle line:90%
everywhere.

00:23:17.240 --> 00:23:19.480 align:middle line:90%
And so this means that the--

00:23:19.480 --> 00:23:21.640 align:middle line:90%
and likewise for the inf.

00:23:21.640 --> 00:23:25.680 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
it's this inequality.

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:30.240 align:middle line:84%
You have to, of course, make it
nice, into a mathematical proof.

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:32.650 align:middle line:84%
But this inequality will
seem kind of obvious.

00:23:32.650 --> 00:23:37.040 align:middle line:90%


00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:41.720 align:middle line:84%
Let me instead try
and prove that if you

00:23:41.720 --> 00:23:46.920 align:middle line:84%
split the integral
up into pieces, then

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:51.080 align:middle line:90%
you can just sum the pieces.

00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:52.580 align:middle line:90%
So this is the following.

00:23:52.580 --> 00:23:58.960 align:middle line:90%


00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:01.280 align:middle line:84%
So again, in the notes,
which I haven't--

00:24:01.280 --> 00:24:03.840 align:middle line:84%
I forgot to post,
but I will post--

00:24:03.840 --> 00:24:07.740 align:middle line:84%
I guess these are posted
because this is from--

00:24:07.740 --> 00:24:11.346 align:middle line:84%
these are things we didn't
quite do yet last time.

00:24:11.346 --> 00:24:16.580 align:middle line:84%
But the proofs of all
of these four here,

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:19.000 align:middle line:84%
also the one in
particular-- like the one,

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:21.620 align:middle line:84%
this one here, I
didn't do now, they

00:24:21.620 --> 00:24:25.140 align:middle line:84%
are all-- the proofs
are all in the notes.

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:30.740 align:middle line:84%
So number 4 here is that
if you take a function,

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:35.080 align:middle line:84%
and it's integrable on
some interval like this,

00:24:35.080 --> 00:24:37.980 align:middle line:90%
it's bounded-- always bounded--

00:24:37.980 --> 00:24:44.660 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at the
integral here of this function,

00:24:44.660 --> 00:24:46.980 align:middle line:90%
and c here is--

00:24:46.980 --> 00:24:49.220 align:middle line:90%
c is somewhere between.

00:24:49.220 --> 00:24:53.220 align:middle line:90%
So c is lying between a and b.

00:24:53.220 --> 00:24:57.400 align:middle line:84%
Well, then, actually--
then, actually,

00:24:57.400 --> 00:25:00.660 align:middle line:84%
let me just full
write down this.

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:03.260 align:middle line:84%
Then the function
here-- if you're

00:25:03.260 --> 00:25:06.660 align:middle line:84%
think about restricting
the function to the smaller

00:25:06.660 --> 00:25:12.660 align:middle line:84%
interval from a to c, it's
also integrable there.

00:25:12.660 --> 00:25:22.000 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, if you restrict
it to the integral from c to b,

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.140 align:middle line:90%
then it's also integrable here.

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:29.240 align:middle line:84%
So it's integrable on
both these subintervals.

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:37.360 align:middle line:84%
And you have that the
integral here of f dx

00:25:37.360 --> 00:25:48.400 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the sum of
the integrals, like that.

00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:52.160 align:middle line:90%


00:25:52.160 --> 00:25:54.050 align:middle line:84%
And so now, why
is this the case?

00:25:54.050 --> 00:25:59.670 align:middle line:90%


00:25:59.670 --> 00:26:02.630 align:middle line:84%
So this is just
because, if you take--

00:26:02.630 --> 00:26:06.600 align:middle line:90%


00:26:06.600 --> 00:26:07.340 align:middle line:90%
so let's see.

00:26:07.340 --> 00:26:22.080 align:middle line:90%


00:26:22.080 --> 00:26:22.580 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:26:22.580 --> 00:26:24.480 align:middle line:90%
So now, let's try to prove that.

00:26:24.480 --> 00:26:34.420 align:middle line:90%


00:26:34.420 --> 00:26:37.980 align:middle line:90%
So right.

00:26:37.980 --> 00:26:40.680 align:middle line:90%
So I want to look at the--

00:26:40.680 --> 00:26:44.860 align:middle line:90%


00:26:44.860 --> 00:26:45.400 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:26:45.400 --> 00:26:52.500 align:middle line:84%
So let me first prove that
if it is integrable here,

00:26:52.500 --> 00:26:55.440 align:middle line:84%
it's also integrable on
these two subintervals.

00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:58.120 align:middle line:90%
And then once we know--

00:26:58.120 --> 00:27:01.340 align:middle line:90%


00:27:01.340 --> 00:27:08.220 align:middle line:84%
in that proof, we will also
see what that sum is equal to.

00:27:08.220 --> 00:27:13.520 align:middle line:84%
So I again use this lemma from
before, that all I need is to--

00:27:13.520 --> 00:27:17.080 align:middle line:84%
for a given epsilon, I
need to find a partition

00:27:17.080 --> 00:27:20.360 align:middle line:84%
so that the spread
between the upper

00:27:20.360 --> 00:27:26.920 align:middle line:84%
and the lower sum for each of
these two is bounded by epsilon.

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:35.440 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon,
since f here is

00:27:35.440 --> 00:27:41.880 align:middle line:84%
integrable on the
interval from a to b,

00:27:41.880 --> 00:27:47.400 align:middle line:84%
we know that there
exists a partition P such

00:27:47.400 --> 00:28:01.030 align:middle line:84%
that the upper sum minus the
lower sum is less than epsilon.

00:28:01.030 --> 00:28:04.960 align:middle line:90%


00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:07.460 align:middle line:90%
Then I look at a refinement.

00:28:07.460 --> 00:28:09.406 align:middle line:90%
So here, I have a.

00:28:09.406 --> 00:28:11.820 align:middle line:90%
Here, I have b.

00:28:11.820 --> 00:28:13.380 align:middle line:90%
And here, I have c.

00:28:13.380 --> 00:28:17.100 align:middle line:90%
And then I have some partition.

00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:20.800 align:middle line:84%
But the partition may not
have c as a dividing point.

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:40.340 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at-- so let's let
P star be the refinement, that

00:28:40.340 --> 00:29:00.220 align:middle line:84%
in addition to all the
dividing points of P,

00:29:00.220 --> 00:29:07.510 align:middle line:90%
also have c as a dividing point.

00:29:07.510 --> 00:29:14.772 align:middle line:90%


00:29:14.772 --> 00:29:16.820 align:middle line:84%
So it has one more
dividing point.

00:29:16.820 --> 00:29:19.900 align:middle line:84%
I mean, of course, it may
be that c was already there.

00:29:19.900 --> 00:29:24.680 align:middle line:84%
Then you don't-- then
this partition is fine.

00:29:24.680 --> 00:29:27.760 align:middle line:84%
And so now-- of
course, now the thing

00:29:27.760 --> 00:29:30.820 align:middle line:84%
is that once you have
that, well, first of all,

00:29:30.820 --> 00:29:32.460 align:middle line:90%
you have-- this is refinement.

00:29:32.460 --> 00:29:35.220 align:middle line:84%
So you still have-- so you
may as well just think--

00:29:35.220 --> 00:29:36.700 align:middle line:90%
so you have this inequality.

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:47.120 align:middle line:84%
So you have that U of f, comma,
P star is minus L of f, P star,

00:29:47.120 --> 00:29:50.380 align:middle line:84%
is also strictly less
than epsilon, right?

00:29:50.380 --> 00:29:53.680 align:middle line:84%
That's because it's
refinement of P.

00:29:53.680 --> 00:29:59.080 align:middle line:84%
And so now you're looking at
the Ps, so this thing here.

00:29:59.080 --> 00:30:01.200 align:middle line:90%
But this thing here--

00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:05.140 align:middle line:84%
this thing here
is just equal to--

00:30:05.140 --> 00:30:11.860 align:middle line:84%
this here is simply
equal to U f of P

00:30:11.860 --> 00:30:24.740 align:middle line:84%
star intersected with
a, c, plus U P, U P

00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:31.200 align:middle line:84%
star, intersected with
the interval from c to b.

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:34.620 align:middle line:84%
By this here, when I'm
taking the partition,

00:30:34.620 --> 00:30:36.800 align:middle line:84%
and I intersect it
with the interval,

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:41.740 align:middle line:84%
I'm just thinking about the
part of the partition that

00:30:41.740 --> 00:30:45.220 align:middle line:90%
is dividing this interval up.

00:30:45.220 --> 00:30:46.500 align:middle line:90%
So you have this.

00:30:46.500 --> 00:30:52.040 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, this
thing here is the sum.

00:30:52.040 --> 00:30:57.620 align:middle line:84%
This one here is the sum of
the partition, the lower sum--

00:30:57.620 --> 00:31:09.456 align:middle line:84%
the sum of the two lower sums,
which is this, a to c, plus L f,

00:31:09.456 --> 00:31:17.640 align:middle line:90%
P star of c to b, like that.

00:31:17.640 --> 00:31:22.348 align:middle line:90%


00:31:22.348 --> 00:31:25.600 align:middle line:84%
And so this, of course,
means that-- so now you

00:31:25.600 --> 00:31:26.880 align:middle line:90%
can split this up.

00:31:26.880 --> 00:31:29.400 align:middle line:84%
And you can divide
by-- so you have--

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:31.360 align:middle line:90%
this is equal to this sum.

00:31:31.360 --> 00:31:33.400 align:middle line:90%
This is equal to that sum.

00:31:33.400 --> 00:31:39.280 align:middle line:84%
So you can just rearrange
it so that this upper sum--

00:31:39.280 --> 00:31:45.030 align:middle line:84%
have. so this means that this
whole thing here is equal to U

00:31:45.030 --> 00:31:52.980 align:middle line:84%
f, P star, intersected
with a, comma, c, minus--

00:31:52.980 --> 00:31:56.120 align:middle line:84%
and then I'll take
this one here next--

00:31:56.120 --> 00:32:05.140 align:middle line:84%
so L f, P star,
intersected with a, c.

00:32:05.140 --> 00:32:07.480 align:middle line:84%
And then I take
plus this one here.

00:32:07.480 --> 00:32:16.780 align:middle line:90%


00:32:16.780 --> 00:32:21.200 align:middle line:84%
And then I take the last
one, which is this one here.

00:32:21.200 --> 00:32:23.820 align:middle line:84%
And it, again, comes
with a minus sign,

00:32:23.820 --> 00:32:34.740 align:middle line:84%
so minus L f, P star,
intersected with c, v,

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:35.620 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:32:35.620 --> 00:32:37.460 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:39.580 align:middle line:90%
But each of these things here--

00:32:39.580 --> 00:32:42.940 align:middle line:90%
this here is non-negative.

00:32:42.940 --> 00:32:46.140 align:middle line:90%
This here is non-negative.

00:32:46.140 --> 00:32:51.180 align:middle line:84%
And you see, the sum
of these two numbers

00:32:51.180 --> 00:32:53.040 align:middle line:90%
is bounded by epsilon.

00:32:53.040 --> 00:32:56.720 align:middle line:84%
So this means that each of them
must be at most epsilon, right?

00:32:56.720 --> 00:32:57.380 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:32:57.380 --> 00:32:59.088 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Would you
able to explain again

00:32:59.088 --> 00:33:01.920 align:middle line:84%
what you did to break up P
star into the intersection of a

00:33:01.920 --> 00:33:02.887 align:middle line:90%
to c and b to c?

00:33:02.887 --> 00:33:03.470 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:33:03.470 --> 00:33:06.400 align:middle line:90%


00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:07.190 align:middle line:90%
So I have--

00:33:07.190 --> 00:33:15.560 align:middle line:90%


00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:17.250 align:middle line:90%
I have here the integral.

00:33:17.250 --> 00:33:21.280 align:middle line:90%


00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:27.200 align:middle line:84%
I have here the
integral from a to b.

00:33:27.200 --> 00:33:30.000 align:middle line:90%
Here, I have c.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:32.920 align:middle line:84%
And the star
partition is the one

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:35.200 align:middle line:84%
that has all of
the dividing points

00:33:35.200 --> 00:33:39.260 align:middle line:84%
of the original partition,
P, and then also c.

00:33:39.260 --> 00:33:43.320 align:middle line:84%
So the partition
looks like this.

00:33:43.320 --> 00:33:46.160 align:middle line:84%
Maybe this here would
be the partition.

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:48.780 align:middle line:90%
And now I'm thinking about--

00:33:48.780 --> 00:33:52.800 align:middle line:90%
so the sum here in the--

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:57.380 align:middle line:84%
the sum from the partition,
it would look like this.

00:33:57.380 --> 00:34:01.500 align:middle line:84%
And I'm summing
over all i, right?

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:04.500 align:middle line:84%
But I can look at where
I'm summing over just

00:34:04.500 --> 00:34:06.370 align:middle line:90%
those intervals, up to here.

00:34:06.370 --> 00:34:08.900 align:middle line:90%


00:34:08.900 --> 00:34:12.340 align:middle line:84%
I can look at where I'm just
summing over this interval.

00:34:12.340 --> 00:34:15.819 align:middle line:84%
And then I can look at where I'm
summing over those intervals.

00:34:15.819 --> 00:34:17.520 align:middle line:90%
And so that's what I mean.

00:34:17.520 --> 00:34:21.780 align:middle line:84%
So this here is now where
you're summing over all the i.

00:34:21.780 --> 00:34:24.179 align:middle line:84%
But you can also
just summing over

00:34:24.179 --> 00:34:28.820 align:middle line:84%
the i's that are less or
equal to c and the it's that

00:34:28.820 --> 00:34:32.020 align:middle line:90%
are in this range, right?

00:34:32.020 --> 00:34:32.730 align:middle line:90%
OK, so that's--

00:34:32.730 --> 00:34:35.586 align:middle line:90%


00:34:35.586 --> 00:34:40.400 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this here proves--

00:34:40.400 --> 00:34:47.100 align:middle line:84%
so what this proves is that
if you take this function,

00:34:47.100 --> 00:34:50.500 align:middle line:84%
and it's integrable
on this interval,

00:34:50.500 --> 00:34:53.780 align:middle line:84%
and you now restrict
it to either of those,

00:34:53.780 --> 00:34:55.800 align:middle line:90%
they are also integrable.

00:34:55.800 --> 00:34:57.840 align:middle line:90%
That's what it actually proves.

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:03.120 align:middle line:84%
But it's easy to
see that it also--

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:06.600 align:middle line:84%
with a little bit-- maybe
I'll leave this for you--

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:09.640 align:middle line:84%
but that through
the proof, we also

00:35:09.640 --> 00:35:12.000 align:middle line:84%
get that this sum
here will have to be

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.480 align:middle line:90%
equal to the sum of these two.

00:35:14.480 --> 00:35:16.600 align:middle line:84%
But really, what I,
technically speaking,

00:35:16.600 --> 00:35:20.552 align:middle line:90%
proved was just this part here.

00:35:20.552 --> 00:35:26.390 align:middle line:84%
But again, all of the details
for this are in the notes.

00:35:26.390 --> 00:35:30.235 align:middle line:90%


00:35:30.235 --> 00:35:33.360 align:middle line:90%
Now, the next thing I want to--

00:35:33.360 --> 00:35:34.560 align:middle line:90%
OK, so yeah.

00:35:34.560 --> 00:35:39.920 align:middle line:84%
So I will-- let's
talk about one other--

00:35:39.920 --> 00:35:41.460 align:middle line:90%
one corollary of this.

00:35:41.460 --> 00:35:46.000 align:middle line:90%


00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:50.760 align:middle line:84%
So it's the corner, really,
not of this fourth property,

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:53.980 align:middle line:90%
but on the third property.

00:35:53.980 --> 00:35:57.400 align:middle line:84%
So the third property
was this with--

00:35:57.400 --> 00:36:02.940 align:middle line:90%


00:36:02.940 --> 00:36:07.120 align:middle line:84%
so the third property was
this property here, over here.

00:36:07.120 --> 00:36:09.880 align:middle line:84%
So I want to talk about a
corollary of this one here.

00:36:09.880 --> 00:36:16.020 align:middle line:90%


00:36:16.020 --> 00:36:18.500 align:middle line:90%
So now I have a function.

00:36:18.500 --> 00:36:20.820 align:middle line:84%
I'm assuming both the
function and the function

00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:22.940 align:middle line:90%
that is the absolute value.

00:36:22.940 --> 00:36:27.180 align:middle line:84%
So the function that's absolute
value means that at each point,

00:36:27.180 --> 00:36:29.140 align:middle line:84%
instead of looking
at f of x, I'm

00:36:29.140 --> 00:36:32.020 align:middle line:84%
looking at the absolute
value of f of x.

00:36:32.020 --> 00:36:33.360 align:middle line:90%
This is the function.

00:36:33.360 --> 00:36:35.980 align:middle line:84%
So I'm assuming that
both of these functions

00:36:35.980 --> 00:36:40.320 align:middle line:84%
are Riemann integrable on
this interval from a to b.

00:36:40.320 --> 00:36:43.060 align:middle line:90%


00:36:43.060 --> 00:36:52.020 align:middle line:84%
And then the claim is that
the integral here of f is less

00:36:52.020 --> 00:36:55.140 align:middle line:90%
or equal-- dx--

00:36:55.140 --> 00:36:59.100 align:middle line:84%
is less or equal to
the integral from a.

00:36:59.100 --> 00:37:00.280 align:middle line:90%
This is a very--

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:06.720 align:middle line:84%
this is very simple inequality,
but extremely useful.

00:37:06.720 --> 00:37:09.360 align:middle line:90%
So this is the claim.

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:11.760 align:middle line:84%
So I'm already assuming
that things are-- everything

00:37:11.760 --> 00:37:12.860 align:middle line:90%
is Riemann integrable.

00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:16.060 align:middle line:84%
So I don't need to prove
anything like that.

00:37:16.060 --> 00:37:18.840 align:middle line:84%
I just need to establish
this inequality.

00:37:18.840 --> 00:37:21.040 align:middle line:84%
And so, to do that,
I'm just looking

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:25.780 align:middle line:84%
at f, where f is less than or
equal to the absolute value.

00:37:25.780 --> 00:37:29.120 align:middle line:84%
If f is positive, it's
equal to the absolute value.

00:37:29.120 --> 00:37:31.860 align:middle line:84%
If it's negative, this here
is non-negative anyway.

00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:34.220 align:middle line:90%
So this is clear.

00:37:34.220 --> 00:37:35.740 align:middle line:90%
This is clearly for all x.

00:37:35.740 --> 00:37:39.520 align:middle line:90%


00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:43.240 align:middle line:84%
But it's also clear that
if I take minus f, you see,

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:44.880 align:middle line:90%
this is also less than this.

00:37:44.880 --> 00:37:48.300 align:middle line:90%


00:37:48.300 --> 00:37:54.540 align:middle line:84%
But now, taken together--
so those two things--

00:37:54.540 --> 00:37:56.580 align:middle line:90%
so now, the first one--

00:37:56.580 --> 00:38:04.060 align:middle line:84%
so let's say star here
and double star here.

00:38:04.060 --> 00:38:12.260 align:middle line:84%
So star here plus property
3 from over there,

00:38:12.260 --> 00:38:17.980 align:middle line:84%
this just gives us that the
integral of f from a to b dx

00:38:17.980 --> 00:38:24.140 align:middle line:84%
is less or equal to the
integral of the absolute value.

00:38:24.140 --> 00:38:27.540 align:middle line:90%
This is from star and 3.

00:38:27.540 --> 00:38:35.340 align:middle line:84%
But if we take double
star here plus 3,

00:38:35.340 --> 00:38:39.200 align:middle line:90%
well, then we have that--

00:38:39.200 --> 00:38:39.840 align:middle line:90%
so this here.

00:38:39.840 --> 00:38:44.820 align:middle line:84%
So we have that the
integral of minus f dx

00:38:44.820 --> 00:38:48.900 align:middle line:84%
is less or equal to
the integral like this.

00:38:48.900 --> 00:38:53.820 align:middle line:90%


00:38:53.820 --> 00:38:57.240 align:middle line:84%
But this one here is-- you
can just think about this here

00:38:57.240 --> 00:38:58.660 align:middle line:90%
as minus 1.

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:04.112 align:middle line:84%
This is like minus 1
times this function.

00:39:04.112 --> 00:39:06.220 align:middle line:90%
So minus 1 just comes out.

00:39:06.220 --> 00:39:07.840 align:middle line:90%
That was like number 1.

00:39:07.840 --> 00:39:11.160 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
like minus 1 times

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:15.400 align:middle line:84%
the integral from
a to b of f dx.

00:39:15.400 --> 00:39:18.200 align:middle line:84%
But this is, of course, the
same as minus the integral

00:39:18.200 --> 00:39:21.420 align:middle line:90%
from a to b f dx.

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:22.860 align:middle line:90%
So you see that--

00:39:22.860 --> 00:39:26.720 align:middle line:84%
so this here-- so
the second here

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:33.040 align:middle line:84%
implies that minus the
integral from a to b f dx

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:36.180 align:middle line:84%
is less or equal
to this thing here.

00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:40.172 align:middle line:90%


00:39:40.172 --> 00:39:45.620 align:middle line:84%
And so now you have this thing
here and that thing here.

00:39:45.620 --> 00:39:49.140 align:middle line:84%
And so, together, it just means
that the absolute value of this

00:39:49.140 --> 00:39:51.580 align:middle line:90%
is bounded by this.

00:39:51.580 --> 00:39:53.330 align:middle line:84%
And so that's
really this corner.

00:39:53.330 --> 00:39:57.400 align:middle line:90%


00:39:57.400 --> 00:39:59.480 align:middle line:84%
The next thing I
want to talk about--

00:39:59.480 --> 00:40:02.060 align:middle line:84%
so this is how to
evaluate integrals.

00:40:02.060 --> 00:40:05.730 align:middle line:84%
And so there, you have the
fundamental theorem of calculus.

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:09.020 align:middle line:90%


00:40:09.020 --> 00:40:12.900 align:middle line:84%
And so we'll give
two versions of that.

00:40:12.900 --> 00:40:22.540 align:middle line:90%
So how to evaluate integrals.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:27.940 align:middle line:90%


00:40:27.940 --> 00:40:30.410 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the fundamental
theorem of calculus.

00:40:30.410 --> 00:40:46.250 align:middle line:90%


00:40:46.250 --> 00:40:48.270 align:middle line:84%
And now, what does the
fundamental theorem

00:40:48.270 --> 00:40:51.830 align:middle line:84%
of calculus-- so
let's give version 1.

00:40:51.830 --> 00:41:02.350 align:middle line:84%
So version 1-- version 1
is that if you take a--

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:15.990 align:middle line:84%
if you take a function, f,
and f here is continuous,

00:41:15.990 --> 00:41:19.830 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking
at the integral--

00:41:19.830 --> 00:41:23.470 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at-- so
you have a function.

00:41:23.470 --> 00:41:28.950 align:middle line:84%
I don't really think
about it as two versions.

00:41:28.950 --> 00:41:36.490 align:middle line:84%
But the version-- but I divided
it into two versions here.

00:41:36.490 --> 00:41:40.030 align:middle line:84%
So the function-- if
f is continuous, say,

00:41:40.030 --> 00:41:42.810 align:middle line:90%
on the interval from--

00:41:42.810 --> 00:41:47.130 align:middle line:84%
on this interval here, and
you define a function, f

00:41:47.130 --> 00:41:58.170 align:middle line:84%
of x, which is the integral
from a to x of f of s ds,

00:41:58.170 --> 00:42:02.170 align:middle line:84%
you see, for each
fixed x in the interval

00:42:02.170 --> 00:42:05.890 align:middle line:84%
here, well, if you're
thinking about the function,

00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:10.150 align:middle line:84%
little f, little f was
continuous on the interval.

00:42:10.150 --> 00:42:12.630 align:middle line:90%
So it's continuous on--

00:42:12.630 --> 00:42:17.690 align:middle line:84%
so f here is continuous on
the interval from a to x.

00:42:17.690 --> 00:42:22.010 align:middle line:84%
So when you restrict it,
it's still continuous.

00:42:22.010 --> 00:42:24.690 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
it's integrable.

00:42:24.690 --> 00:42:28.130 align:middle line:84%
And so this here
gives you a number.

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:31.970 align:middle line:84%
And so, for each x, you can
think about this number here.

00:42:31.970 --> 00:42:34.970 align:middle line:84%
So this gives you a
function, capital F.

00:42:34.970 --> 00:42:39.150 align:middle line:84%
And the claim is that
this function here--

00:42:39.150 --> 00:42:46.190 align:middle line:84%
so the claim is that the
function capital F, defined

00:42:46.190 --> 00:42:49.570 align:middle line:90%
this way, is differentiable.

00:42:49.570 --> 00:42:52.210 align:middle line:90%
So capital F is differentiable.

00:42:52.210 --> 00:42:57.310 align:middle line:90%


00:42:57.310 --> 00:43:12.670 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative of this
at x is little f of x.

00:43:12.670 --> 00:43:13.950 align:middle line:90%
And maybe I'll just--

00:43:13.950 --> 00:43:14.590 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:43:14.590 --> 00:43:15.900 align:middle line:90%
So that's the claim.

00:43:15.900 --> 00:43:19.670 align:middle line:90%


00:43:19.670 --> 00:43:21.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:21.710 --> 00:43:23.010 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to prove that.

00:43:23.010 --> 00:43:30.350 align:middle line:90%


00:43:30.350 --> 00:43:32.870 align:middle line:90%
So let's look at--

00:43:32.870 --> 00:43:34.080 align:middle line:90%
let's try to prove--

00:43:34.080 --> 00:43:37.250 align:middle line:90%


00:43:37.250 --> 00:43:39.370 align:middle line:90%
so we want to prove--

00:43:39.370 --> 00:43:42.700 align:middle line:84%
so we want to prove that this
function-- so we want to prove--

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:45.650 align:middle line:90%


00:43:45.650 --> 00:44:04.170 align:middle line:84%
so we want to show that f
prime exists at, say, at x0.

00:44:04.170 --> 00:44:07.310 align:middle line:84%
If you want to prove
that it exists,

00:44:07.310 --> 00:44:10.437 align:middle line:84%
then you need to look at
the difference quotient.

00:44:10.437 --> 00:44:12.520 align:middle line:84%
So we'll need to look at
this difference quotient.

00:44:12.520 --> 00:44:16.330 align:middle line:90%


00:44:16.330 --> 00:44:18.570 align:middle line:84%
And we need to prove
that this thing here

00:44:18.570 --> 00:44:21.350 align:middle line:90%
has a limit as x goes to x0.

00:44:21.350 --> 00:44:22.890 align:middle line:90%
So x0 is fixed.

00:44:22.890 --> 00:44:25.320 align:middle line:84%
And you want to prove that
it has a limit, right?

00:44:25.320 --> 00:44:31.115 align:middle line:90%


00:44:31.115 --> 00:44:35.670 align:middle line:84%
So in order to estimate
this, let me just--

00:44:35.670 --> 00:44:38.390 align:middle line:90%
let me not divide first.

00:44:38.390 --> 00:44:42.430 align:middle line:84%
Let me just look at what
this difference here is.

00:44:42.430 --> 00:44:46.630 align:middle line:84%
And then, afterwards, I'm
going to divide by x minus x0.

00:44:46.630 --> 00:44:50.510 align:middle line:84%
So if I'm looking at this,
let's, for the sake of argument,

00:44:50.510 --> 00:44:54.110 align:middle line:90%
assume that x is bigger than x0.

00:44:54.110 --> 00:44:58.470 align:middle line:84%
Of course, I need to also
see when I'm approaching x0

00:44:58.470 --> 00:45:00.350 align:middle line:90%
from the other side.

00:45:00.350 --> 00:45:03.170 align:middle line:84%
But the argument
for that is similar.

00:45:03.170 --> 00:45:09.270 align:middle line:84%
So I just assume that
x is bigger than x0.

00:45:09.270 --> 00:45:11.930 align:middle line:90%
Well, this difference here--

00:45:11.930 --> 00:45:15.390 align:middle line:84%
well, the function--
so this function here,

00:45:15.390 --> 00:45:17.390 align:middle line:84%
the function here-- so
let me just write it over

00:45:17.390 --> 00:45:20.910 align:middle line:84%
here so I have a
little more space.

00:45:20.910 --> 00:45:23.950 align:middle line:84%
So this difference here,
where the function-- this

00:45:23.950 --> 00:45:30.910 align:middle line:84%
here is the integral
from a to x f of s ds.

00:45:30.910 --> 00:45:41.210 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here is the
integral from a to x0 f of s ds,

00:45:41.210 --> 00:45:43.130 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:45:43.130 --> 00:45:49.210 align:middle line:84%
But this first integral here,
I can use this fourth rule

00:45:49.210 --> 00:45:51.190 align:middle line:90%
that I maybe don't have anymore.

00:45:51.190 --> 00:45:55.970 align:middle line:84%
But the fourth rule is saying
that you can split it up.

00:45:55.970 --> 00:45:57.630 align:middle line:84%
An integral, you
can split it up.

00:45:57.630 --> 00:46:01.690 align:middle line:84%
So here, if you have
a, then you have x0,

00:46:01.690 --> 00:46:06.690 align:middle line:84%
and then you have x, if you want
to integrate little f over this,

00:46:06.690 --> 00:46:09.250 align:middle line:84%
it's the same as
integrating over this

00:46:09.250 --> 00:46:11.770 align:middle line:90%
plus the integral over that.

00:46:11.770 --> 00:46:13.070 align:middle line:90%
So I do that.

00:46:13.070 --> 00:46:16.210 align:middle line:84%
So this one here, I
break into two pieces.

00:46:16.210 --> 00:46:21.970 align:middle line:84%
I integrate from
a to x0 f of s ds.

00:46:21.970 --> 00:46:24.870 align:middle line:84%
And then I take
the second piece,

00:46:24.870 --> 00:46:32.230 align:middle line:84%
which is from x0 to x, and
then minus the integral from a

00:46:32.230 --> 00:46:36.190 align:middle line:90%
to x0 of f of s ds.

00:46:36.190 --> 00:46:38.550 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:46:38.550 --> 00:46:41.430 align:middle line:84%
But now you see
that this one here

00:46:41.430 --> 00:46:43.690 align:middle line:90%
cancels out with that, right?

00:46:43.690 --> 00:46:51.050 align:middle line:84%
And so this difference is just
the integral from x0 to x f of s

00:46:51.050 --> 00:46:51.550 align:middle line:90%
ds.

00:46:51.550 --> 00:46:59.242 align:middle line:90%


00:46:59.242 --> 00:47:09.190 align:middle line:84%
So what we have is we have
that this difference here,

00:47:09.190 --> 00:47:13.830 align:middle line:90%
f of x minus f of x0--

00:47:13.830 --> 00:47:19.710 align:middle line:84%
we know that this difference
here is equal to this integral

00:47:19.710 --> 00:47:20.210 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:47:20.210 --> 00:47:24.470 align:middle line:90%


00:47:24.470 --> 00:47:30.690 align:middle line:84%
Now, let me use this to bound
this thing here from above

00:47:30.690 --> 00:47:31.920 align:middle line:90%
and bound it from below.

00:47:31.920 --> 00:47:35.890 align:middle line:90%


00:47:35.890 --> 00:47:39.730 align:middle line:84%
You see, this integral
here, this function here--

00:47:39.730 --> 00:47:45.516 align:middle line:84%
so this function here, if you're
looking at this integral here

00:47:45.516 --> 00:47:50.650 align:middle line:84%
of f of s ds,
well, this function

00:47:50.650 --> 00:47:57.690 align:middle line:90%
here is smaller than the max--

00:47:57.690 --> 00:48:00.730 align:middle line:84%
the function is continuous, so
the max and sup is the same--

00:48:00.730 --> 00:48:05.210 align:middle line:84%
the max, or the sup, or whatever
you want, on that interval.

00:48:05.210 --> 00:48:14.690 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is less than
the integral of, if you will, x0

00:48:14.690 --> 00:48:20.510 align:middle line:84%
to x of the sup of f
on this interval here.

00:48:20.510 --> 00:48:24.690 align:middle line:90%


00:48:24.690 --> 00:48:27.010 align:middle line:90%
But this is just a constant.

00:48:27.010 --> 00:48:29.960 align:middle line:90%
And so this here is just--

00:48:29.960 --> 00:48:33.190 align:middle line:84%
this is just like the
sup of the function

00:48:33.190 --> 00:48:37.230 align:middle line:90%
on this little interval times--

00:48:37.230 --> 00:48:38.770 align:middle line:90%
so this here's a constant.

00:48:38.770 --> 00:48:40.590 align:middle line:90%
So this just pops out.

00:48:40.590 --> 00:48:43.210 align:middle line:84%
And then it's just the
integral of 1 on this.

00:48:43.210 --> 00:48:45.190 align:middle line:84%
But that's just the
length of the interval.

00:48:45.190 --> 00:48:48.230 align:middle line:84%
So this is this here times
the length of the interval.

00:48:48.230 --> 00:48:53.096 align:middle line:84%
And the length of
the interval is this.

00:48:53.096 --> 00:48:58.118 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is less than that.

00:48:58.118 --> 00:49:02.350 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, this function
here on this little interval

00:49:02.350 --> 00:49:05.370 align:middle line:90%
is bigger or equal to the inf.

00:49:05.370 --> 00:49:10.550 align:middle line:84%
So this is bigger
than if you were just

00:49:10.550 --> 00:49:14.100 align:middle line:84%
integrating the inf of the
function on this same interval.

00:49:14.100 --> 00:49:17.150 align:middle line:90%


00:49:17.150 --> 00:49:20.750 align:middle line:84%
But the inf-- this
is just a constant.

00:49:20.750 --> 00:49:22.190 align:middle line:90%
This pops out.

00:49:22.190 --> 00:49:26.410 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is just the inf

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:31.530 align:middle line:84%
of the function on
this interval here

00:49:31.530 --> 00:49:37.750 align:middle line:84%
times the length of the
interval, like that.

00:49:37.750 --> 00:49:40.876 align:middle line:90%


00:49:40.876 --> 00:49:44.210 align:middle line:84%
So now I can-- and remember
that this thing here

00:49:44.210 --> 00:49:46.690 align:middle line:90%
was equal to the difference.

00:49:46.690 --> 00:49:48.790 align:middle line:90%
So now I can just record this.

00:49:48.790 --> 00:49:52.690 align:middle line:90%
So what I have is now--

00:49:52.690 --> 00:49:58.330 align:middle line:84%
what I'm interested in is in
the difference in capital F.

00:49:58.330 --> 00:50:01.230 align:middle line:90%
So what I'm interested in is--

00:50:01.230 --> 00:50:04.610 align:middle line:84%
of course, I really want to
look at the difference quotient.

00:50:04.610 --> 00:50:06.590 align:middle line:84%
But I can do this
in just a second.

00:50:06.590 --> 00:50:10.930 align:middle line:84%
So I'm interested in the
difference of the function

00:50:10.930 --> 00:50:13.390 align:middle line:90%
at those two points.

00:50:13.390 --> 00:50:18.290 align:middle line:84%
I know that that difference is
equal to that integral here.

00:50:18.290 --> 00:50:23.130 align:middle line:84%
And that integral is bounded
from above by this and below

00:50:23.130 --> 00:50:24.010 align:middle line:90%
by that.

00:50:24.010 --> 00:50:25.170 align:middle line:90%
So I just write--

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:28.250 align:middle line:84%
I can now just write that
this difference here--

00:50:28.250 --> 00:50:31.030 align:middle line:84%
maybe I should write it so
I have a little more space.

00:50:31.030 --> 00:50:36.470 align:middle line:84%
Somehow, F of x minus
F of x0, the difference

00:50:36.470 --> 00:50:42.990 align:middle line:84%
is bounded from above by this
thing here, the sup of f,

00:50:42.990 --> 00:50:48.430 align:middle line:84%
on this little interval,
times x minus x0.

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:55.110 align:middle line:84%
And it's bounded
from below by the inf

00:50:55.110 --> 00:51:02.430 align:middle line:84%
on that same interval times
the length of the interval.

00:51:02.430 --> 00:51:06.110 align:middle line:90%


00:51:06.110 --> 00:51:08.630 align:middle line:84%
So now we can go to
the difference quotient

00:51:08.630 --> 00:51:12.030 align:middle line:84%
because we just divide by
x minus x0 on both sides.

00:51:12.030 --> 00:51:14.750 align:middle line:90%
x is bigger than x0.

00:51:14.750 --> 00:51:17.430 align:middle line:90%
So you have this thing here.

00:51:17.430 --> 00:51:19.490 align:middle line:84%
So you have this
difference quotient here.

00:51:19.490 --> 00:51:22.890 align:middle line:84%
And that's what we want
to show has a limit.

00:51:22.890 --> 00:51:26.010 align:middle line:84%
And now we have that
this is less than sup

00:51:26.010 --> 00:51:30.290 align:middle line:84%
of f on this little
interval here.

00:51:30.290 --> 00:51:34.450 align:middle line:84%
And it's bigger or
equal to the inf of f

00:51:34.450 --> 00:51:35.920 align:middle line:90%
on that same little interval.

00:51:35.920 --> 00:51:39.520 align:middle line:90%


00:51:39.520 --> 00:51:43.650 align:middle line:90%
But you see that as x here--

00:51:43.650 --> 00:51:44.560 align:middle line:90%
but now you have--

00:51:44.560 --> 00:51:48.930 align:middle line:90%


00:51:48.930 --> 00:51:51.680 align:middle line:84%
now you have that
as x goes to x0--

00:51:51.680 --> 00:52:02.790 align:middle line:90%


00:52:02.790 --> 00:52:11.130 align:middle line:84%
so now, as x goes
to x0, the values--

00:52:11.130 --> 00:52:15.570 align:middle line:84%
and not just the value at x, but
actually, in this whole interval

00:52:15.570 --> 00:52:16.210 align:middle line:90%
here--

00:52:16.210 --> 00:52:20.970 align:middle line:84%
the values goes to what
the values is at x0.

00:52:20.970 --> 00:52:26.070 align:middle line:84%
So you see that this here,
the right-hand side here, goes

00:52:26.070 --> 00:52:29.190 align:middle line:90%
to f of x-- little f of x0.

00:52:29.190 --> 00:52:34.430 align:middle line:84%
And the left-hand side
goes to little f of x0.

00:52:34.430 --> 00:52:37.130 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this thing
is squeezed between these two

00:52:37.130 --> 00:52:37.630 align:middle line:90%
numbers.

00:52:37.630 --> 00:52:39.210 align:middle line:90%
That goes to the same number.

00:52:39.210 --> 00:52:42.290 align:middle line:84%
So this difference
quotient also goes--

00:52:42.290 --> 00:52:47.950 align:middle line:84%
so this difference
quotient here goes

00:52:47.950 --> 00:52:54.190 align:middle line:84%
to f of x0, because
it's squeezed

00:52:54.190 --> 00:52:59.150 align:middle line:84%
between those two numbers that
converge to the same number--

00:52:59.150 --> 00:53:03.470 align:middle line:84%
namely, to f of x--
little f of x0, right?

00:53:03.470 --> 00:53:08.630 align:middle line:84%
So this here proves that it's--
but technically speaking,

00:53:08.630 --> 00:53:13.950 align:middle line:84%
I only did it where I'm assuming
that x was bigger than x0.

00:53:13.950 --> 00:53:18.570 align:middle line:84%
If you let-- so you
also need to check

00:53:18.570 --> 00:53:21.290 align:middle line:84%
when x is strictly
less than x0, and it's

00:53:21.290 --> 00:53:25.010 align:middle line:90%
converging to x0 from below.

00:53:25.010 --> 00:53:30.240 align:middle line:84%
But with trivial modification,
the same proof works.

00:53:30.240 --> 00:53:32.830 align:middle line:84%
And that's done
out in the notes.

00:53:32.830 --> 00:53:34.920 align:middle line:90%
So I will not go through that.

00:53:34.920 --> 00:53:38.430 align:middle line:90%


00:53:38.430 --> 00:53:40.150 align:middle line:90%
Now let's talk about--

00:53:40.150 --> 00:53:43.970 align:middle line:84%
so this is the second version
of the fundamental theorem

00:53:43.970 --> 00:53:44.500 align:middle line:90%
of calculus.

00:53:44.500 --> 00:53:51.810 align:middle line:90%


00:53:51.810 --> 00:53:55.890 align:middle line:84%
And so-- again,
you wouldn't really

00:53:55.890 --> 00:53:58.250 align:middle line:84%
eventually think
about it, probably,

00:53:58.250 --> 00:54:00.330 align:middle line:90%
as two different versions.

00:54:00.330 --> 00:54:07.410 align:middle line:84%
But they're slightly-- it's two
things about the same stuff.

00:54:07.410 --> 00:54:09.510 align:middle line:90%
But the second version here--

00:54:09.510 --> 00:54:11.670 align:middle line:84%
So I divided it into
these two versions.

00:54:11.670 --> 00:54:14.810 align:middle line:90%
So the second version--

00:54:14.810 --> 00:54:26.650 align:middle line:84%
so again, fundamental theorem
of calculus, version 2.

00:54:26.650 --> 00:54:30.230 align:middle line:90%


00:54:30.230 --> 00:54:32.950 align:middle line:90%
And so this is the following--

00:54:32.950 --> 00:54:37.790 align:middle line:84%
that you take a function,
F, that is defined--

00:54:37.790 --> 00:54:46.950 align:middle line:84%
and F is defined on some
interval from a to b into R.

00:54:46.950 --> 00:54:50.510 align:middle line:90%
And F is differentiable.

00:54:50.510 --> 00:54:53.350 align:middle line:90%
So this here exists.

00:54:53.350 --> 00:54:57.070 align:middle line:84%
It's differentiable
at each point.

00:54:57.070 --> 00:55:04.330 align:middle line:84%
And f here, this little
f, is Riemann integrable.

00:55:04.330 --> 00:55:09.630 align:middle line:90%


00:55:09.630 --> 00:55:19.050 align:middle line:84%
And then the claim is that
F of b minus capital F at a

00:55:19.050 --> 00:55:28.790 align:middle line:84%
is the integral from a
to b of little f of x dx.

00:55:28.790 --> 00:55:29.770 align:middle line:90%
So that's the claim.

00:55:29.770 --> 00:55:40.422 align:middle line:90%


00:55:40.422 --> 00:55:45.870 align:middle line:84%
I wonder if I should
just skip that.

00:55:45.870 --> 00:55:50.270 align:middle line:84%
I did the proof for this
out in the notes also.

00:55:50.270 --> 00:55:52.000 align:middle line:90%
So maybe I'll just skip that.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:56.730 align:middle line:90%


00:55:56.730 --> 00:56:04.930 align:middle line:84%
And then-- OK, so now-- but
let me look at an example

00:56:04.930 --> 00:56:06.670 align:middle line:90%
where I'm applying it.

00:56:06.670 --> 00:56:19.870 align:middle line:90%


00:56:19.870 --> 00:56:21.710 align:middle line:90%
And so I have--

00:56:21.710 --> 00:56:26.550 align:middle line:84%
I'm looking at-- so
suppose I want to compute

00:56:26.550 --> 00:56:30.910 align:middle line:90%
x squared from 0 to 1 dx.

00:56:30.910 --> 00:56:34.710 align:middle line:90%
Suppose I want to compute that.

00:56:34.710 --> 00:56:37.370 align:middle line:84%
And so, in this case,
I could look at--

00:56:37.370 --> 00:56:40.350 align:middle line:84%
so if I want to
apply that version,

00:56:40.350 --> 00:56:42.070 align:middle line:84%
I could think
about-- suppose I'm

00:56:42.070 --> 00:56:49.256 align:middle line:84%
looking at F of x equal to
x to the power 3 over 3.

00:56:49.256 --> 00:56:51.590 align:middle line:90%
Suppose I'm looking at this.

00:56:51.590 --> 00:56:54.310 align:middle line:84%
Well, if I'm looking
at this function,

00:56:54.310 --> 00:56:59.630 align:middle line:84%
I know that capital F of x is
equal to the derivative of this.

00:56:59.630 --> 00:57:01.550 align:middle line:90%
It's just x squared.

00:57:01.550 --> 00:57:02.670 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:57:02.670 --> 00:57:05.950 align:middle line:84%
So this, say-- and x
squared is now-- of course,

00:57:05.950 --> 00:57:07.130 align:middle line:90%
it's continuous.

00:57:07.130 --> 00:57:09.110 align:middle line:90%
So it's integrable.

00:57:09.110 --> 00:57:13.610 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
by the second--

00:57:13.610 --> 00:57:34.610 align:middle line:84%
by this second version of the
fundamental theorem of calculus,

00:57:34.610 --> 00:57:42.290 align:middle line:84%
then we have that
F of 1 minus F of 0

00:57:42.290 --> 00:57:47.470 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the integral
of the derivative,

00:57:47.470 --> 00:57:51.770 align:middle line:84%
because the derivative
is integrable, so 0 to 1,

00:57:51.770 --> 00:57:57.170 align:middle line:90%
of x squared dx.

00:57:57.170 --> 00:58:01.810 align:middle line:84%
But this here is now just
evaluating this function here.

00:58:01.810 --> 00:58:06.010 align:middle line:90%
So this here is 1/3 minus 0.

00:58:06.010 --> 00:58:08.650 align:middle line:84%
So this original
integral is 1/3.

00:58:08.650 --> 00:58:13.035 align:middle line:90%


00:58:13.035 --> 00:58:13.535 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:13.535 --> 00:58:16.750 align:middle line:90%


00:58:16.750 --> 00:58:19.990 align:middle line:90%
So the next thing--

00:58:19.990 --> 00:58:28.330 align:middle line:84%
so the next thing I want to talk
about is improper integrals.

00:58:28.330 --> 00:58:30.690 align:middle line:84%
So this here
concludes-- this here

00:58:30.690 --> 00:58:33.230 align:middle line:84%
was stuff I actually had
from the previous lecture.

00:58:33.230 --> 00:58:35.450 align:middle line:84%
That was why I skipped
a couple of things.

00:58:35.450 --> 00:58:39.630 align:middle line:90%


00:58:39.630 --> 00:58:43.470 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, but the details
for the things I skipped

00:58:43.470 --> 00:58:45.010 align:middle line:90%
is in the notes.

00:58:45.010 --> 00:58:47.430 align:middle line:84%
And the things I skipped
is very similar to things

00:58:47.430 --> 00:58:49.040 align:middle line:90%
I went through here, anyway.

00:58:49.040 --> 00:58:53.030 align:middle line:90%


00:58:53.030 --> 00:58:56.470 align:middle line:84%
So now, let me look
at improper integrals.

00:58:56.470 --> 00:59:00.310 align:middle line:84%
And there is a couple
of versions of this.

00:59:00.310 --> 00:59:02.910 align:middle line:84%
So we will look at
two versions of this.

00:59:02.910 --> 00:59:05.590 align:middle line:90%
One is where the integral--

00:59:05.590 --> 00:59:07.250 align:middle line:90%
where the integral is--

00:59:07.250 --> 00:59:09.710 align:middle line:84%
so we will look at
improper integrals.

00:59:09.710 --> 00:59:18.170 align:middle line:90%


00:59:18.170 --> 00:59:21.240 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to look at two
versions, so two versions.

00:59:21.240 --> 00:59:28.090 align:middle line:90%


00:59:28.090 --> 00:59:33.870 align:middle line:84%
Version 1 is where the
integral is unbounded.

00:59:33.870 --> 00:59:39.590 align:middle line:90%
The integral is unbounded.

00:59:39.590 --> 00:59:43.490 align:middle line:90%


00:59:43.490 --> 00:59:47.510 align:middle line:84%
And the second version is where
the function is unbounded.

00:59:47.510 --> 00:59:57.156 align:middle line:90%


00:59:57.156 --> 01:00:02.650 align:middle line:84%
Now, in the first
version, then you take--

01:00:02.650 --> 01:00:08.750 align:middle line:90%
you're looking at a function, f.

01:00:08.750 --> 01:00:12.310 align:middle line:90%
And this function is integrable.

01:00:12.310 --> 01:00:23.010 align:middle line:84%
So f here is integrable
from a to b for all--

01:00:23.010 --> 01:00:26.150 align:middle line:90%


01:00:26.150 --> 01:00:29.310 align:middle line:90%
so a here is fixed.

01:00:29.310 --> 01:00:34.330 align:middle line:84%
But it's integrable for
all b bigger than a.

01:00:34.330 --> 01:00:35.410 align:middle line:90%
So a is fixed.

01:00:35.410 --> 01:00:36.600 align:middle line:90%
So a here, fixed.

01:00:36.600 --> 01:00:39.310 align:middle line:90%


01:00:39.310 --> 01:00:42.710 align:middle line:90%
And it's integrable like that.

01:00:42.710 --> 01:00:44.910 align:middle line:90%
Then what we want to--

01:00:44.910 --> 01:00:49.190 align:middle line:90%
what we are interested in--

01:00:49.190 --> 01:00:53.296 align:middle line:84%
so again, if you're thinking
about the integral as a--

01:00:53.296 --> 01:00:56.860 align:middle line:84%
think about the integral
as the weighted area.

01:00:56.860 --> 01:00:59.482 align:middle line:90%


01:00:59.482 --> 01:01:02.150 align:middle line:84%
And weight just means
that if the function is

01:01:02.150 --> 01:01:05.770 align:middle line:84%
negative in a
stretch, then the area

01:01:05.770 --> 01:01:08.570 align:middle line:84%
there will count
with a minus sign.

01:01:08.570 --> 01:01:12.650 align:middle line:84%
So this here is-- so what
we're interested in is

01:01:12.650 --> 01:01:16.290 align:middle line:84%
we were interested
in making sense

01:01:16.290 --> 01:01:21.530 align:middle line:84%
of the area, the weighted
area below the graph, where we

01:01:21.530 --> 01:01:24.810 align:middle line:90%
go all the way out to infinity.

01:01:24.810 --> 01:01:26.390 align:middle line:90%
And so this is--

01:01:26.390 --> 01:01:27.520 align:middle line:90%
does this make sense?

01:01:27.520 --> 01:01:35.090 align:middle line:90%


01:01:35.090 --> 01:01:38.230 align:middle line:84%
So this is, in this case,
the improper integral.

01:01:38.230 --> 01:01:41.982 align:middle line:84%
It's improper because it's
not a bounded interval.

01:01:41.982 --> 01:01:45.290 align:middle line:90%
And so yes, if--

01:01:45.290 --> 01:01:55.330 align:middle line:84%
yes, if this limit here of
a to b, If this limit here

01:01:55.330 --> 01:02:00.970 align:middle line:84%
of f of x dx, if this limit
here as b goes to infinity

01:02:00.970 --> 01:02:13.110 align:middle line:84%
exists, then we say that
the improper integral here

01:02:13.110 --> 01:02:19.310 align:middle line:84%
from a to infinity of f of x--
we say that this here exists

01:02:19.310 --> 01:02:21.040 align:middle line:90%
and is equal to this limit.

01:02:21.040 --> 01:02:33.780 align:middle line:90%


01:02:33.780 --> 01:02:37.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is one version of
the improper integrals.

01:02:37.110 --> 01:02:39.550 align:middle line:90%
And the other version is--

01:02:39.550 --> 01:02:42.630 align:middle line:84%
the other version of
the improper integral

01:02:42.630 --> 01:02:43.650 align:middle line:90%
is the following.

01:02:43.650 --> 01:02:51.190 align:middle line:90%


01:02:51.190 --> 01:02:54.270 align:middle line:90%
So the second version--

01:02:54.270 --> 01:02:57.250 align:middle line:84%
so this is where f
here is unbounded.

01:02:57.250 --> 01:03:00.410 align:middle line:90%


01:03:00.410 --> 01:03:03.530 align:middle line:84%
In a minute, I'll look at
examples of both things.

01:03:03.530 --> 01:03:05.650 align:middle line:90%
So the function is unbounded.

01:03:05.650 --> 01:03:07.210 align:middle line:90%
So it's defined.

01:03:07.210 --> 01:03:14.970 align:middle line:84%
But f here is supposed to be
integrable on, say, a to b.

01:03:14.970 --> 01:03:20.770 align:middle line:84%
Right, so a is supposed
to be integrable from--

01:03:20.770 --> 01:03:33.210 align:middle line:84%
it's supposed to be integrable
from c to b for all c

01:03:33.210 --> 01:03:34.610 align:middle line:90%
bigger than--

01:03:34.610 --> 01:03:40.810 align:middle line:84%
so c here, where c is bigger
than a and less than b.

01:03:40.810 --> 01:03:44.370 align:middle line:90%
So think here about--

01:03:44.370 --> 01:03:46.810 align:middle line:90%
here, you have a.

01:03:46.810 --> 01:03:47.830 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have b.

01:03:47.830 --> 01:03:51.010 align:middle line:84%
So a and b, in this
case, are fixed.

01:03:51.010 --> 01:03:54.330 align:middle line:90%
But the function is not bounded.

01:03:54.330 --> 01:03:57.810 align:middle line:84%
It's not maybe even
defined at a, right?

01:03:57.810 --> 01:03:59.450 align:middle line:90%
It's not really defined at a.

01:03:59.450 --> 01:04:02.096 align:middle line:90%


01:04:02.096 --> 01:04:05.750 align:middle line:90%
But it is integrable on--

01:04:05.750 --> 01:04:09.430 align:middle line:84%
if you go anywhere
strictly to the right of a,

01:04:09.430 --> 01:04:15.550 align:middle line:84%
then it is integrable
on this interval here.

01:04:15.550 --> 01:04:22.990 align:middle line:84%
And so if this limit-- so
if this limit here as c goes

01:04:22.990 --> 01:04:29.430 align:middle line:84%
to a, the integral from
c to b of f of x dx--

01:04:29.430 --> 01:04:36.110 align:middle line:84%
if this limit here exists,
then we say that this improper

01:04:36.110 --> 01:04:42.230 align:middle line:84%
integral from c to b--
sorry, a to b, of f of x dx--

01:04:42.230 --> 01:04:45.590 align:middle line:84%
this is an improper integral
because the function is not

01:04:45.590 --> 01:04:47.870 align:middle line:90%
bounded on this whole interval.

01:04:47.870 --> 01:04:50.990 align:middle line:90%
It's not even defined at a.

01:04:50.990 --> 01:04:54.030 align:middle line:84%
If this here-- we say
that this thing here

01:04:54.030 --> 01:05:02.830 align:middle line:84%
is equal to this limit as c
goes to a of c, b, f of x dx.

01:05:02.830 --> 01:05:05.362 align:middle line:90%


01:05:05.362 --> 01:05:13.970 align:middle line:84%
And so the improper integral
actually often appear in things.

01:05:13.970 --> 01:05:18.450 align:middle line:84%
So let me look at
examples of this.

01:05:18.450 --> 01:05:20.590 align:middle line:84%
So I will look at
example of this.

01:05:20.590 --> 01:05:22.250 align:middle line:84%
And I will look--
so again, there's

01:05:22.250 --> 01:05:26.770 align:middle line:84%
these two versions, where
the interval is unbounded,

01:05:26.770 --> 01:05:29.310 align:middle line:90%
or the function is unbounded.

01:05:29.310 --> 01:05:32.030 align:middle line:84%
Of course, there's all
kinds of variation of this.

01:05:32.030 --> 01:05:34.690 align:middle line:84%
Here, I looked at
where the function

01:05:34.690 --> 01:05:37.810 align:middle line:90%
was unbounded to the left.

01:05:37.810 --> 01:05:40.050 align:middle line:84%
But you could do the
same to the right.

01:05:40.050 --> 01:05:47.230 align:middle line:84%
It could be this interval
here, this interval in the--

01:05:47.230 --> 01:05:50.010 align:middle line:84%
where the interval
was unbounded.

01:05:50.010 --> 01:05:55.030 align:middle line:84%
I'm talking-- I was when
I explained what it means,

01:05:55.030 --> 01:06:00.910 align:middle line:84%
I did it as if the interval
was unbounded to the right.

01:06:00.910 --> 01:06:04.430 align:middle line:84%
But of course, you could also
look at unbounded to the left,

01:06:04.430 --> 01:06:06.030 align:middle line:84%
or you could even
look at where it

01:06:06.030 --> 01:06:08.670 align:middle line:84%
was unbounded both to the
right and to the left.

01:06:08.670 --> 01:06:13.462 align:middle line:90%


01:06:13.462 --> 01:06:15.540 align:middle line:84%
But let me look
at some examples.

01:06:15.540 --> 01:06:26.630 align:middle line:90%


01:06:26.630 --> 01:06:29.790 align:middle line:90%
And so the first example--

01:06:29.790 --> 01:06:33.670 align:middle line:84%
again, the first two
examples would be where

01:06:33.670 --> 01:06:37.376 align:middle line:90%
the interval is unbounded.

01:06:37.376 --> 01:06:47.670 align:middle line:90%


01:06:47.670 --> 01:06:54.210 align:middle line:84%
So this first example here is
where the interval is unbounded.

01:06:54.210 --> 01:06:58.970 align:middle line:84%
And we're looking at the
interval is 1 to infinity.

01:06:58.970 --> 01:07:01.570 align:middle line:84%
And we're looking
at the function, f

01:07:01.570 --> 01:07:04.680 align:middle line:90%
of x equal to 1 over x squared.

01:07:04.680 --> 01:07:09.115 align:middle line:90%


01:07:09.115 --> 01:07:12.370 align:middle line:90%
And I'm interested in--

01:07:12.370 --> 01:07:19.410 align:middle line:84%
and the question is, does the
improper integral, this here,

01:07:19.410 --> 01:07:23.200 align:middle line:84%
of 1 over x squared
dx, does this exist?

01:07:23.200 --> 01:07:26.090 align:middle line:90%


01:07:26.090 --> 01:07:29.250 align:middle line:90%
That's the question.

01:07:29.250 --> 01:07:35.410 align:middle line:84%
And so we use the fundamental
theorem of calculus

01:07:35.410 --> 01:07:37.090 align:middle line:90%
to determine that.

01:07:37.090 --> 01:07:39.770 align:middle line:84%
We observe that if
we're looking at f

01:07:39.770 --> 01:07:48.090 align:middle line:84%
of x, which is 1 over x,
then the derivative here,

01:07:48.090 --> 01:07:51.200 align:middle line:84%
of this function here,
this is 1 over x squared.

01:07:51.200 --> 01:07:54.526 align:middle line:90%


01:07:54.526 --> 01:07:56.370 align:middle line:90%
So this is what we observe.

01:07:56.370 --> 01:08:02.470 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, it means that if
you're integrating from 1 to b

01:08:02.470 --> 01:08:06.710 align:middle line:84%
of 1 over x squared
dx, this thing here

01:08:06.710 --> 01:08:11.390 align:middle line:84%
is the same as f
of b minus f of 1.

01:08:11.390 --> 01:08:14.270 align:middle line:90%


01:08:14.270 --> 01:08:18.149 align:middle line:84%
And so, using this,
and we know what f is,

01:08:18.149 --> 01:08:19.769 align:middle line:90%
you have that this is minus--

01:08:19.769 --> 01:08:22.790 align:middle line:90%


01:08:22.790 --> 01:08:28.750 align:middle line:90%
minus, sorry, 1 over b and--

01:08:28.750 --> 01:08:29.729 align:middle line:90%
no, sorry.

01:08:29.729 --> 01:08:31.410 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, it's minus 1 over b.

01:08:31.410 --> 01:08:33.229 align:middle line:90%
This is what you get from this.

01:08:33.229 --> 01:08:39.510 align:middle line:84%
And here, you're getting 1,
plus 1, like this, right?

01:08:39.510 --> 01:08:43.710 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this thing
here, as b goes to infinity,

01:08:43.710 --> 01:08:45.630 align:middle line:90%
this has converged to 0.

01:08:45.630 --> 01:08:47.830 align:middle line:90%
So this has converged to 1.

01:08:47.830 --> 01:08:50.370 align:middle line:90%
So indeed, this improper?

01:08:50.370 --> 01:08:54.210 align:middle line:90%
Yes is the answer.

01:08:54.210 --> 01:09:03.050 align:middle line:84%
And what it's equal to,
because it converts to 1,

01:09:03.050 --> 01:09:05.210 align:middle line:90%
it's equal to 1.

01:09:05.210 --> 01:09:08.210 align:middle line:84%
So again, if you're
thinking about it,

01:09:08.210 --> 01:09:09.970 align:middle line:84%
it's a little bit
like what we did

01:09:09.970 --> 01:09:14.590 align:middle line:84%
for series that you're summing
infinitely many numbers.

01:09:14.590 --> 01:09:16.609 align:middle line:84%
So here, you're
looking at something.

01:09:16.609 --> 01:09:19.050 align:middle line:90%
And you're looking at the area.

01:09:19.050 --> 01:09:21.210 align:middle line:84%
But the area actually
is finite, even

01:09:21.210 --> 01:09:22.719 align:middle line:90%
though it continues on forever.

01:09:22.719 --> 01:09:26.890 align:middle line:90%


01:09:26.890 --> 01:09:28.630 align:middle line:90%
So that's one version of it.

01:09:28.630 --> 01:09:32.390 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that instead
of 1 over x squared--

01:09:32.390 --> 01:09:37.130 align:middle line:84%
so 1 over the property that the
function 1 over x squared has

01:09:37.130 --> 01:09:40.729 align:middle line:84%
is that it goes really
quite fast to 0.

01:09:40.729 --> 01:09:44.130 align:middle line:84%
As x goes to infinity,
1 over x squared

01:09:44.130 --> 01:09:48.350 align:middle line:90%
goes really pretty fast to 0.

01:09:48.350 --> 01:09:52.109 align:middle line:84%
Suppose I look at a
function that does go to 0.

01:09:52.109 --> 01:09:55.590 align:middle line:84%
But if it doesn't go
to 0, if the function

01:09:55.590 --> 01:09:58.110 align:middle line:90%
doesn't go to 0, if we kind of--

01:09:58.110 --> 01:10:01.630 align:middle line:84%
let's say that we're staying
above a certain line.

01:10:01.630 --> 01:10:03.310 align:middle line:84%
Well, then the area
below the graph

01:10:03.310 --> 01:10:05.570 align:middle line:84%
would, of course, be
larger than this thing.

01:10:05.570 --> 01:10:07.210 align:middle line:90%
And that would be infinite.

01:10:07.210 --> 01:10:09.560 align:middle line:90%
So it's not going to converge.

01:10:09.560 --> 01:10:15.550 align:middle line:84%
So it will have to
go to 0 in some way.

01:10:15.550 --> 01:10:18.990 align:middle line:84%
So example 2, I'm looking
at another function.

01:10:18.990 --> 01:10:20.430 align:middle line:90%
Still goes to 0.

01:10:20.430 --> 01:10:24.710 align:middle line:84%
Again, the interval is the
same from 1 to infinity.

01:10:24.710 --> 01:10:28.910 align:middle line:84%
And the function is now--
this time, it's 1 over x.

01:10:28.910 --> 01:10:30.250 align:middle line:90%
It still goes to 0.

01:10:30.250 --> 01:10:31.610 align:middle line:90%
So maybe it has a chance.

01:10:31.610 --> 01:10:34.310 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

01:10:34.310 --> 01:10:40.390 align:middle line:84%
If you now take the
integral from 1 to x of--

01:10:40.390 --> 01:10:47.050 align:middle line:84%
1 to b, sorry, of 1 over
x dx, well, again, you

01:10:47.050 --> 01:10:49.230 align:middle line:84%
use the fundamental
theorem of calculus.

01:10:49.230 --> 01:10:50.730 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking
at the function,

01:10:50.730 --> 01:11:01.010 align:middle line:84%
f of x equal to log of x, the
derivative of log is 1 over x.

01:11:01.010 --> 01:11:04.630 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here, by the
fundamental theorem of calculus,

01:11:04.630 --> 01:11:07.370 align:middle line:84%
this second version of
fundamental theorem of calculus

01:11:07.370 --> 01:11:11.330 align:middle line:90%
is f of b minus f of 1.

01:11:11.330 --> 01:11:17.370 align:middle line:84%
And that is log of
b minus log of 1.

01:11:17.370 --> 01:11:19.230 align:middle line:90%
Log of 1 is 0.

01:11:19.230 --> 01:11:21.370 align:middle line:90%
So this is just log of b.

01:11:21.370 --> 01:11:25.570 align:middle line:84%
But as b goes to infinity,
this here actually goes--

01:11:25.570 --> 01:11:26.750 align:middle line:90%
it's not bounded.

01:11:26.750 --> 01:11:29.450 align:middle line:84%
It tends to wander
off to infinity.

01:11:29.450 --> 01:11:38.500 align:middle line:84%
So this improper integral here,
this one here, does not exist.

01:11:38.500 --> 01:11:43.710 align:middle line:90%


01:11:43.710 --> 01:11:46.150 align:middle line:84%
It's like the area
below this function

01:11:46.150 --> 01:11:51.230 align:middle line:84%
here would actually
be infinite, right?

01:11:51.230 --> 01:11:53.770 align:middle line:90%
It does not go to 0 fast enough.

01:11:53.770 --> 01:12:00.950 align:middle line:84%
So that's examples of where
the interval is unbounded.

01:12:00.950 --> 01:12:05.870 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that we look at examples
where the state of the interval

01:12:05.870 --> 01:12:07.250 align:middle line:90%
is being unbounded.

01:12:07.250 --> 01:12:09.750 align:middle line:90%
The function is unbounded.

01:12:09.750 --> 01:12:11.970 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at some
examples of that.

01:12:11.970 --> 01:12:14.870 align:middle line:90%


01:12:14.870 --> 01:12:23.150 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you take-- so now,
suppose you take the interval

01:12:23.150 --> 01:12:24.550 align:middle line:90%
from--

01:12:24.550 --> 01:12:25.990 align:middle line:90%
so the interval is bounded.

01:12:25.990 --> 01:12:32.110 align:middle line:84%
But the function
is not unbounded.

01:12:32.110 --> 01:12:34.310 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, the function--
the interval is bounded.

01:12:34.310 --> 01:12:36.710 align:middle line:90%
But the function is unbounded.

01:12:36.710 --> 01:12:40.790 align:middle line:84%
So I'm looking at,
first, f of x equal to 1

01:12:40.790 --> 01:12:43.090 align:middle line:90%
over square root of x.

01:12:43.090 --> 01:12:49.270 align:middle line:84%
As x goes to 0, square
root of x goes to 0.

01:12:49.270 --> 01:12:51.830 align:middle line:84%
So this means that 1
over it goes to infinity.

01:12:51.830 --> 01:12:54.570 align:middle line:90%
So this function is not bounded.

01:12:54.570 --> 01:12:56.730 align:middle line:84%
But if I'm now
looking at-- so I want

01:12:56.730 --> 01:12:58.930 align:middle line:84%
to look at the improper
integral, where

01:12:58.930 --> 01:13:01.050 align:middle line:90%
I'm taking this function.

01:13:01.050 --> 01:13:06.170 align:middle line:84%
The function is blowing up
as I'm going close to 0,

01:13:06.170 --> 01:13:07.730 align:middle line:90%
blowing up like that.

01:13:07.730 --> 01:13:12.290 align:middle line:84%
And I want to see,
does this here--

01:13:12.290 --> 01:13:17.130 align:middle line:84%
does this improper
integral here--

01:13:17.130 --> 01:13:18.060 align:middle line:90%
does this exist?

01:13:18.060 --> 01:13:22.127 align:middle line:90%


01:13:22.127 --> 01:13:22.960 align:middle line:90%
That's the question.

01:13:22.960 --> 01:13:26.090 align:middle line:90%


01:13:26.090 --> 01:13:29.130 align:middle line:84%
And so, in order
to figure that out,

01:13:29.130 --> 01:13:33.410 align:middle line:84%
I use the fundamental
theorem of calculus again.

01:13:33.410 --> 01:13:37.090 align:middle line:90%
So if I take the function--

01:13:37.090 --> 01:13:41.190 align:middle line:84%
if I take the
function, f of x is

01:13:41.190 --> 01:13:45.120 align:middle line:84%
equal to 2 times
square root of x,

01:13:45.120 --> 01:13:51.550 align:middle line:84%
and I now take the
derivative of this,

01:13:51.550 --> 01:13:53.470 align:middle line:84%
then I get 1 over
square root of x.

01:13:53.470 --> 01:13:56.350 align:middle line:90%


01:13:56.350 --> 01:13:58.830 align:middle line:90%
And so this means that--

01:13:58.830 --> 01:14:01.680 align:middle line:84%
so this means that
if you now look at--

01:14:01.680 --> 01:14:12.350 align:middle line:90%


01:14:12.350 --> 01:14:15.670 align:middle line:84%
so this means that if you're
now looking at the integral

01:14:15.670 --> 01:14:18.830 align:middle line:90%
here of--

01:14:18.830 --> 01:14:22.390 align:middle line:90%


01:14:22.390 --> 01:14:28.390 align:middle line:84%
this integral from a, say, to
1 of 1 over square root of x--

01:14:28.390 --> 01:14:30.910 align:middle line:90%
a is strictly positive--

01:14:30.910 --> 01:14:32.470 align:middle line:90%
dx.

01:14:32.470 --> 01:14:42.170 align:middle line:84%
This thing here is capital
F of 1 minus capital F of a.

01:14:42.170 --> 01:14:45.730 align:middle line:84%
And so capital F was
this function here.

01:14:45.730 --> 01:14:48.090 align:middle line:90%
So this is 2, right?

01:14:48.090 --> 01:14:51.810 align:middle line:84%
2-- square root of 1
plus 1, so that's 2--

01:14:51.810 --> 01:14:56.810 align:middle line:90%
minus 2 square root of a.

01:14:56.810 --> 01:15:01.310 align:middle line:84%
But now, as a goes to 0,
this here converts to 2.

01:15:01.310 --> 01:15:04.180 align:middle line:84%
So this improper
integral exists.

01:15:04.180 --> 01:15:04.680 align:middle line:90%
So yes.

01:15:04.680 --> 01:15:07.850 align:middle line:90%


01:15:07.850 --> 01:15:15.590 align:middle line:84%
This one here exists
and is equal to 2.

01:15:15.590 --> 01:15:20.430 align:middle line:90%


01:15:20.430 --> 01:15:26.460 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at one
last example of this.

01:15:26.460 --> 01:15:46.990 align:middle line:90%


01:15:46.990 --> 01:15:51.870 align:middle line:84%
And so this is another example
where the function is-- so

01:15:51.870 --> 01:15:58.170 align:middle line:84%
again, in this sort of example,
the function was unbounded.

01:15:58.170 --> 01:16:00.590 align:middle line:90%
It's blowing up.

01:16:00.590 --> 01:16:02.090 align:middle line:90%
It's going to infinity.

01:16:02.090 --> 01:16:05.270 align:middle line:84%
But the area below the graph--
that's where we calculated--

01:16:05.270 --> 01:16:08.150 align:middle line:90%
is still actually finite.

01:16:08.150 --> 01:16:12.520 align:middle line:84%
But what if the function is
blowing up faster than this?

01:16:12.520 --> 01:16:18.110 align:middle line:84%
So this is an example like
this, that if you take--

01:16:18.110 --> 01:16:21.470 align:middle line:84%
it's, again, the
interval from 0 to 1.

01:16:21.470 --> 01:16:23.390 align:middle line:84%
And the function
is now-- now it's

01:16:23.390 --> 01:16:28.830 align:middle line:84%
going to infinite
faster as x goes to 0.

01:16:28.830 --> 01:16:31.470 align:middle line:90%
So this is the function.

01:16:31.470 --> 01:16:35.690 align:middle line:84%
And so now we want-- what
we're again asking is,

01:16:35.690 --> 01:16:43.056 align:middle line:84%
does the improper integral-- so
does this improper integral here

01:16:43.056 --> 01:16:43.556 align:middle line:90%
exist?

01:16:43.556 --> 01:16:48.050 align:middle line:90%


01:16:48.050 --> 01:16:51.430 align:middle line:84%
And let's see if
it exists or not.

01:16:51.430 --> 01:16:54.570 align:middle line:84%
So we use the fundamental
theorem of calculus again.

01:16:54.570 --> 01:16:57.610 align:middle line:84%
We observe that the
function, F of x

01:16:57.610 --> 01:17:02.770 align:middle line:84%
equal to log of x, that the
derivative of this function

01:17:02.770 --> 01:17:04.730 align:middle line:90%
is just 1 over x.

01:17:04.730 --> 01:17:08.550 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if
we integrate from a-- a

01:17:08.550 --> 01:17:14.570 align:middle line:84%
is now, again, strictly
positive, strictly positive.

01:17:14.570 --> 01:17:19.610 align:middle line:84%
So if we're looking
at this integral here,

01:17:19.610 --> 01:17:22.090 align:middle line:84%
this here is-- because
of the second version

01:17:22.090 --> 01:17:24.850 align:middle line:84%
of the fundamental theorem
of calculus, we have

01:17:24.850 --> 01:17:30.230 align:middle line:84%
that this here is F
in 1 minus F in a.

01:17:30.230 --> 01:17:33.190 align:middle line:90%


01:17:33.190 --> 01:17:39.150 align:middle line:84%
And this thing is now
log of 1-- that's 0--

01:17:39.150 --> 01:17:41.670 align:middle line:90%
minus log of a.

01:17:41.670 --> 01:17:43.790 align:middle line:90%
Log of a is--

01:17:43.790 --> 01:17:47.910 align:middle line:84%
right, so log of a--
so this is like that.

01:17:47.910 --> 01:17:51.670 align:middle line:84%
But now, remember that
the log function here--

01:17:51.670 --> 01:17:55.170 align:middle line:84%
the log function
looks like this.

01:17:55.170 --> 01:17:58.390 align:middle line:90%
This is the log function.

01:17:58.390 --> 01:18:02.950 align:middle line:84%
So you see that as
you go towards 0 here,

01:18:02.950 --> 01:18:05.930 align:middle line:84%
this number here goes
to minus infinity.

01:18:05.930 --> 01:18:08.630 align:middle line:90%
So this here goes to infinity.

01:18:08.630 --> 01:18:11.350 align:middle line:90%
So it doesn't converge.

01:18:11.350 --> 01:18:13.850 align:middle line:90%
So the answer is no.

01:18:13.850 --> 01:18:19.936 align:middle line:90%


01:18:19.936 --> 01:18:25.670 align:middle line:84%
And so the very last thing
I want to talk about is,

01:18:25.670 --> 01:18:28.150 align:middle line:90%
I'll just give you a definition.

01:18:28.150 --> 01:18:29.720 align:middle line:90%
So this is arc length.

01:18:29.720 --> 01:18:33.650 align:middle line:90%


01:18:33.650 --> 01:18:38.200 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you take
a curve in the plane.

01:18:38.200 --> 01:18:44.690 align:middle line:90%


01:18:44.690 --> 01:18:48.660 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that I have
a curve in the plane.

01:18:48.660 --> 01:18:56.490 align:middle line:90%


01:18:56.490 --> 01:19:00.290 align:middle line:90%
So gamma of t.

01:19:00.290 --> 01:19:01.630 align:middle line:90%
This is a curve.

01:19:01.630 --> 01:19:03.370 align:middle line:90%
So it has-- in the plane.

01:19:03.370 --> 01:19:07.530 align:middle line:84%
So it means that it has two
coordinates called gamma of s.

01:19:07.530 --> 01:19:09.220 align:middle line:84%
I think that's what
I did in the notes.

01:19:09.220 --> 01:19:12.370 align:middle line:90%


01:19:12.370 --> 01:19:15.810 align:middle line:90%
So this here is the curve.

01:19:15.810 --> 01:19:22.630 align:middle line:84%
And I'm assuming that f
and g are differentiable.

01:19:22.630 --> 01:19:25.210 align:middle line:90%


01:19:25.210 --> 01:19:31.130 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative
here are continuous.

01:19:31.130 --> 01:19:33.870 align:middle line:90%


01:19:33.870 --> 01:19:35.950 align:middle line:90%
So suppose I have such a curve.

01:19:35.950 --> 01:19:41.590 align:middle line:84%
And s here is running in
an interval from a to b.

01:19:41.590 --> 01:19:45.950 align:middle line:84%
Then the length of the
curve is, by definition,

01:19:45.950 --> 01:19:54.270 align:middle line:84%
the integral from a to b
of square root of f prime

01:19:54.270 --> 01:20:04.550 align:middle line:84%
of s squared plus g
prime of s squared ds.

01:20:04.550 --> 01:20:07.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
length of the curve.

01:20:07.530 --> 01:20:11.630 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I'll talk a little bit
more about that next time.

01:20:11.630 --> 01:20:12.490 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:20:12.490 --> 01:20:14.510 align:middle line:90%
So I'll stop here.

01:20:14.510 --> 01:20:19.310 align:middle line:90%
And I'll post the notes.

01:20:19.310 --> 01:20:22.350 align:middle line:90%
Any questions?

01:20:22.350 --> 01:20:25.060 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

01:20:25.060 --> 01:20:28.000 align:middle line:90%